Title:
Turn on block at first sight (Microsoft Defender Antivirus / Microsoft Defender for Endpoint)

Type:
Documentation

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This Microsoft Learn article explains “Block at first sight” (BAFS), a Microsoft Defender Antivirus next-gen protection feature that rapidly blocks previously unseen malware using cloud-delivered analysis.  
- It addresses the gap between local signature/heuristic detection and emerging threats by querying Microsoft’s cloud backend and optionally uploading suspicious samples for automated analysis.  
- The write-up details prerequisites (cloud protection enabled, automatic sample submission, up-to-date Defender platform) and clarifies that BAFS primarily applies to Internet-originated executables and certain non-PE content (JS/VBS/macros).  
- It covers operational behavior such as temporarily preventing execution (“cloud block timeout”) while the cloud makes a determination, and notes that response time can drop from hours to seconds.  
- Configuration guidance is provided for enterprise deployment via Microsoft Intune and Group Policy, plus verification steps on endpoints via Windows Security settings.  
- Useful mainly for Blue Teams/endpoint admins, but also relevant to Red Teams for understanding cloud-based execution gating and where “Mark-of-the-Web/Internet Zone” provenance affects detonation.

Technical Focus:
- Microsoft Defender Antivirus cloud-delivered protection (MAPS)
- Automatic sample submission and cloud backend automated analysis
- Internet Zone / Mark-of-the-Web (MOTW) influence on scanning decisions
- Cloud block timeout / execution lock while verdict is pending
- Intune Endpoint Security (Antivirus policy) configuration
- Group Policy settings under Defender Antivirus \> MAPS

Use Cases:
- Deploying BAFS enterprise-wide via Intune to reduce time-to-block for new malware
- Hardening endpoints by enforcing cloud protection + automatic sample submission
- Validating endpoint posture (confirming cloud-delivered protection and sample submission are enabled)
- Tuning user impact by adjusting cloud block timeout and customizing block notifications
- Assessing attacker tradecraft constraints around Internet-originated payload execution

Keywords:
Microsoft Defender Antivirus, Microsoft Defender for Endpoint, Block at First Sight, BAFS, cloud-delivered protection, MAPS, automatic sample submission, cloud backend, machine learning, heuristics, automated analysis, Mark-of-the-Web, Internet Zone, non-PE files, JS, VBS, macros, Intune Endpoint security, Group Policy, cloud block timeout